            </div>
            <div type="translation" ana="b1">
                <p>One (is) the God. Monument (belonging) first to Sammaseos, (the subdeacon), who
                    died 25 years ago; (and) then to Loulianos, 5 years old, and to (his) brother
                    Stephanos, 2 years old, (both) sons of Antys. (The two children) passed away on
                    the same day and hour, having a good faith, in (the) year 367, on (the) 22nd day
                    of the month of Panemos, on (the) 3rd day (Tuesday). Be of good cheer, no one
                    (is) immortal.</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary" ana="b1">
                <p>This epitaph is significant because it provides valuable information on both
                    Zooran funerary customs and the identity of the tomb owners and their
                    relationships with other people whose epitaphs have been found. The
                    prosopographical and chronological data offered, combined with other published
                    epitaphs, suggest that these three men were members of the same family. There is
                    a strong possibility that Loulianos and Stephanos were the great-nephews of
                    Sammaseos. It is quite possible that their father Antys outlived his two sons
                    and did not yet have his own tomb, impelling him to bury them with his
                    uncle.</p>
            </div>
